### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the [existing issues](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues)
- [X] I have read the [guide to filing a bug](https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports)

### Use case

There is a situation where I want to display a separator after the last item in ListView.separated. Currently, the separator is only displayed in the gap between the items. I would like to be able to control whether or not the separator is displayed after the last item.

### Proposal

BAD
```Dart
Column(
  children: [
    ListView.separated(
      shrinkWrap: true,
      itemCount: 25,
      separatorBuilder: (BuildContext context, int index) => const Divider(),
      itemBuilder: (BuildContext context, int index) {
        return ListTile(
          title: Text('item $index'),
        );
      },
    ),
    const Divider(),
  ],
);
```

GOOD
```Dart
ListView.separated(
  includeLast: true
  itemCount: 25,
  separatorBuilder: (BuildContext context, int index) => const Divider(),
  itemBuilder: (BuildContext context, int index) {
    return ListTile(
      title: Text('item $index'),
    );
  },
);
```

### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the [existing issues](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues)
- [X] I have read the [guide to filing a bug](https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports)

### Use case

Currently, the Flutter AutofillGroup lacks the ability to differentiate between user-inputted data and autofilled content, such as, in customized password input fields. This deficiency becomes problematic when developers incorporate a "show password" feature, introducing a potential security vulnerability. When autofill is employed, in conjunction with the "show password" functionality, it inadvertently exposes the password.

If an individual inputs their credentials and grants the browser permission to save this information, a subsequent user accessing the application from the same browser can exploit autofill to access the saved username/password combination. This user can then click on the "show password" option, thereby exposing the password.

```
AutoFillGroup(

  // Username
  child: TextField / TextFormField(
  ...
   autofillHints: const [AutofillHints.username, AutofillHints.email, AutofillHints.newPassword],
  ...
  ),
  
  // Password field
  TextField / TextFormField(
     ...
      autofillHints: const [AutofillHints.password],
     ...
  )
)
```


### Proposal

Improve Flutter's AutofillGroup by introducing either a controller or callback for autofill event detection, or by providing additional data to the TextField's onChange function or the TextFormField controller. This enhancement empowers developers to differentiate between autofill and user input, ensuring the secure implementation of "show password" features while safeguarding user data privacy.

The following 2 proposals have no preference, it's just to possible options

**Option A**
Consider 'bool autofilled ' parameter within onChange or a TextFormField's controller to identify Autofill-triggered value changes.


```
AutoFillGroup(
  // Username
  child: TextField / TextFormField(

  onChange(value, autofilled){ ... }
  ...
   autofillHints: const [AutofillHints.username, AutofillHints.email, AutofillHints.newPassword],
  ...
  ),
  
  // Password field
  TextField / TextFormField(
      onChange(value, autofilled){ 
         // disableShowPass functionality
      }
      ...
      autofillHints: const [AutofillHints.password],
     ...
  )
)
```



**Option B**
Enhance Flutter's AutofillGroup with a controller or callback to detect autofill events, enabling secure "show password" features while safeguarding user data privacy.

Implementation Consideration
For a seamless sequence, delay the AutofillGroup's onAutofill event until after autofill completes in the TextField to ensure the effectiveness of disabling the custom "show password" feature.

```
AutoFillGroup(
  onAutofill: (AutoFillGroupEvent event){
    // disable show password functionality based upon event
  },
  // Username
  child: TextField / TextFormField(

  onChange(value, autofilled){ ... }
  ...
   autofillHints: const [AutofillHints.username, AutofillHints.email, AutofillHints.newPassword],
  ...
  ),
  
  // Password field
  TextField / TextFormField(
  onChange(value, autofilled){ ... }
     ...
      autofillHints: const [AutofillHints.password],
     ...
  )
)
```

### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the [existing issues](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues)
- [X] I have read the [guide to filing a bug](https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports)

### Use case

I have this snippet:


<details>

<summary>Code sample</summary>

You can also checkout https://github.com/ValentinVignal/flutter_app_stable/tree/flutter/size-transition-height-factor

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      theme: ThemeData.light(useMaterial3: true),
      darkTheme: ThemeData.dark(useMaterial3: true),
      home: const MyHomePage(),
    );
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyHomePage({super.key});

  @override
  State<MyHomePage> createState() => _MyHomePageState();
}

class _MyHomePageState extends State<MyHomePage> {
  var _visible = true;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      body: Center(
        child: ColoredBox(
          color: Theme.of(context).colorScheme.secondaryContainer,
          child: AnimatedSwitcher(
            duration: const Duration(milliseconds: 300),
            transitionBuilder: (child, animation) {
              return SizeTransition(
                sizeFactor: animation,
                axis: Axis.vertical,
                child: child,
              );
            },
            child: _visible
                ? ColoredBox(
                    color: Theme.of(context).colorScheme.primaryContainer,
                    child: const SizedBox(
                      height: 200,
                      width: 200,
                      child: Center(
                        child: Text('Hello World'),
                      ),
                    ),
                  )
                : const SizedBox(),
          ),
        ),
      ),
      floatingActionButton: FloatingActionButton(
        onPressed: () {
          setState(() {
            _visible = !_visible;
          });
        },
        child: const Icon(Icons.add),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

</details>


<details>

<summary>Video</summary>

https://github.com/flutter/flutter/assets/32538273/9dd6c91d-6a3c-424b-9e5a-8069ebf87d19


</details>

In the video the animation is vertical. The other axis (horizontal) is stretched and uses the entire available space.
I would like my `primaryContainer` to be centered and only use the width of its child (200 px).
I want the `secondaryContainer` to shrink and be the same size as the `primaryContainer` (and therefore hidden).

### Proposal

Add a new parameter to `SizeTransition` (ex: `crossAxisSizeFactor`) 

https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/622c2b2b07217335cb0fda5447fa0c0b46ecfab8/packages/flutter/lib/src/widgets/transitions.dart#L444-L450

```diff
  class SizeTransition extends AnimatedWidget {
    const SizeTransition({
      // ...
+     this.crossAxisSizeFactor,
    }) : super(listenable: sizeFactor);
    // ... 
+   final double? crossAxisSizeFactor;
  }
```

and pass it to the cross axis of the `Align` widget:

https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/622c2b2b07217335cb0fda5447fa0c0b46ecfab8/packages/flutter/lib/src/widgets/transitions.dart#L492-L499


```diff
      return ClipRect(
        child: Align(
          alignment: alignment,
-         heightFactor: axis == Axis.vertical ? math.max(sizeFactor.value, 0.0) : null,
+         heightFactor: axis == Axis.vertical ? math.max(sizeFactor.value, 0.0) : crossAxisSizeFactor,
-         widthFactor: axis == Axis.horizontal ? math.max(sizeFactor.value, 0.0) : null,
+         widthFactor: axis == Axis.horizontal ? math.max(sizeFactor.value, 0.0) : crossAxisSizeFactor,
          child: child,
        ),
      );
```

In my code sample, I would use 

```dart
crossAxisSizeFactor : 1,
```


And this gives me the output:

<details>

<summary>Video</summary>


https://github.com/flutter/flutter/assets/32538273/4b06c19c-a75c-4189-a52e-454879548690



</details>

### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the [existing issues](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues)
- [X] I have read the [guide to filing a bug](https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports)

### Use case

In a screen containing a relatively long `Form` in a `SingleChildScrollView`, we want to bring the user's attention to the field that may cause a validation error after calling `FormState.validate()`. The solution was as follows:
```
  void _validateForm(BuildContext context) {
    if (_fomKey.currentState!.validate()) {
      fun();
    } else {
      WidgetsBinding.instance.addPostFrameCallback((_) {
        if (_someWidgetKey.currentContext != null && _someWidgetKey.currentContext!.mounted) {
          Scrollable.ensureVisible(
            _someWidgetKey.currentContext!,
          );
        }
      });
    }
  }
```

Now the problem is that where there are multiple widgets that may cause a validation error. There's currently no way to detect which one we should scroll to.
The only solution is to implement a custom validation logic, which defies the whole purpose of using `Form`

### Proposal

The proposal is to have another version of the `validate` method, let's call it, `validateGranularly` (naming suggestions are very welcome) that returns `Map<Key, bool>`, so the above problem will be addressed as follows:

```
  void _validateForm(BuildContext context) {
    if (_fomKey.currentState!.validate()) {
      fun();
    } else {
      Key invalidFieldKey =  
      _fomKey.currentState!.validateGranularly().firstWehere((e) => !e) // e==false
      WidgetsBinding.instance.addPostFrameCallback((_) {
        if (invalidFieldKey .currentContext != null && invalidFieldKey .currentContext!.mounted) {
          Scrollable.ensureVisible(
            invalidFieldKey .currentContext!,
          );
        }
      });
    }
  }

### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the [existing issues](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues)
- [X] I have read the [guide to filing a bug](https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports)

### Use case

Create a simple way for something like a `ListView` to be pinch-zoomed. This is a somewhat common pattern with a list of vertical images. If the images contain text then a user may want to zoom the entire list itself rather than each image when the user gets to it. Two concrete examples I can think of are a comic reader and reviewing a list of documents before submitting them. In the case of the former I am aware of at least one flutter app with millions of installs that already does this (not affiliated). Since that app is not open source I don't know how they did it but I suspect that they may have written their own custom `Viewport` for it. As for ways which this can be done now, they are all somewhat limited. The most obvious place to start would be a `ListView` warped in a `InteractiveViewer`: 
<details open>

<summary>naive method</summary>

```dart
InteractiveViewer(
  child: ListView.builder(
    itemCount: 100,
    itemBuilder: (context, index) {
      return Center(child: Text("text $index"));
    }
  ),
)
```
</details>

<details>

<summary>naive method video</summary>


https://github.com/flutter/flutter/assets/92773903/a6ccd7e3-160f-457b-a3ef-f71fbe7db99b


</details>

There is a major issue with this method, however.  The  zoom event in the `InteractiveViewer` may be swallowed by the `ListView` scroll physics. (https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/65006) This can be solved by setting `physics` to `NeverScrollableScrollPhysics()`  when two fingers are on the screen using a `Listener` widget (https://cloud.tencent.com/developer/ask/sof/107381999). 

<details>

<summary>Listener solution</summary>

```dart
Listener(
  onPointerDown: (event) {
    events.add(event.pointer);
    print("new event");
  },
  onPointerUp: (event) {
    events.clear();
    print("events cleared");
    setState(() {
      canScroll = true;
    });
  },
  onPointerMove: (event) {
    if (events.length == 2) {
      setState(() {
        canScroll = false;
      });
    }
  },
  child: SizedBox(
    height: 600,
    width: 300,
    child: InteractiveViewer(
      child: ListView.builder(
          physics:  canScroll
              ? const ScrollPhysics()
              : const NeverScrollableScrollPhysics(),
          itemCount: 10000000,
          itemBuilder: (context, index) {
            return Container(
              //enable to observe that the list rebuilds on every scroll
              //color: Colors.primaries[Random().nextInt(Colors.primaries.length)],
              child: Center(
                  child: Text("text $index")
              ),
            );
          }
      ),
    ),
  ),
)
```
</details>


<details>

<summary>Listener method video</summary>




https://github.com/flutter/flutter/assets/92773903/9a0e1017-d7b4-4aa9-98b0-ad1b58a50af7



</details>

There are still some more major issues:
1. sometimes the `ListView` is scrolling, meaning that you can't pan diagonally (as we are not panning at all, rather scrolling) and sometimes the `InteractiveViewer` is "scrolling" (ie. panning) meaning that it will run out of available view to scroll and not continue down the list. (Usually the Listview is in control.) This is shown in the above video.
2. When zoomed in you cannot pan to the top of the viewport, meaning you cannot view the first 10 px or so of the list.  (https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/68073). Observed in the above video.
3. The list is rebuilt on every scroll (enable the color in the container to observe). This turned out to be the worst drawback of all listed here. It is caused by the rebuild and this problem exists with zoom_widget as well which also needs the Listener workaround. I should mention that I am not using a plain List in production and this could be why performance is worse there as the build may be more expensive. I am also using images in the production list so that could be why. The examples given here already exhibit the other three issues however so I don't think the usecase should be rejected because of this fact. Removing the `Listener` makes the list mostly smooth again, but recreates the first issue.  Adding "`SingleFingerScrollPhysics`" or something to `ListView` could help here. This isn't a great general solution though. Implementing (https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/65006#issuecomment-858590637) for `InteractiveViewer` is slightly better.
4. It needs a set height (there are ways to solve this, however, perhaps with `LayoutBuilder` or similar)
 
One package sugested in some stackoverflow posts is https://pub.dev/packages/photo_view but this has an issue when trying to scroll a list as well (https://github.com/bluefireteam/photo_view/issues/392).

Combining the `Listener` method with the `Zoom` widget (https://pub.dev/packages/zoom_widget) fixes the second issue (and creates some new ones).

<details>
<summary>Zoom solution</summary>

```dart
import 'dart:math';
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:zoom_widget/zoom_widget.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      home: const MyHomePage(),
    );
  }
}

class MyHomePage extends StatefulWidget {
  const MyHomePage({super.key});
  @override
  State<MyHomePage> createState() => _MyHomePageState();
}

class _MyHomePageState extends State<MyHomePage> {
  final events = [];
  bool canScroll = true;
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
        body: Listener(
          onPointerDown: (event) {
            events.add(event.pointer);
            print("new event");
          },
          onPointerUp: (event) {
            events.clear();
            print("events cleared");
            setState(() {
              canScroll = true;
            });
          },
          onPointerMove: (event) {
            if (events.length == 2) {
              setState(() {
                canScroll = false;
              });
            }
          },
          child: Zoom(
            maxZoomWidth: MediaQuery.of(context).size.width,
            opacityScrollBars: 0.0,
            centerOnScale: true,
            maxZoomHeight: 600,
            doubleTapZoom: true,
            enableScroll: true,
            child: ListView.builder(
                physics:  canScroll
                    ? const ScrollPhysics()
                    : const NeverScrollableScrollPhysics(),
                itemCount: 10000000,
                itemBuilder: (context, index) {
                  return Container(
                    //enable to observe that the list rebuilds on every scroll
                    //color: Colors.primaries[Random().nextInt(Colors.primaries.length)],
                    child: Center(
                        child: Text("text $index")
                    ),
                  );
                }
            ),
          ),
        )
    );
  }
}
```
</details>

I think in general this warrants a more first class method – I believe this is handled 'natively' in android `RecyclerVIew` with `ScaleGestureDetector` and with `UIScrollView` with `UIImageView` on iOS (comments here welcome, I haven't tested either of these).  Consider that zooming "just works" on web browsers, and must be actively disabled by the developer to change that behavior (not to say we need to act like browsers by default, mobile apps admittedly generally _don't_ need to be zoomed).

this seems to be a somewhat popular request:

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/73538288/flutter-how-to-create-list-of-zoomable-images
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/76777474/vertical-direction-zooming-not-working-when-listview-is-wrapped-with-interactive
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/76331178/how-to-pinch-to-zoom-listview-in-flutter
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/68392068/could-not-complete-vertical-scroll-of-listview-inside-interactiveviewer
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/64326715/flutter-interactiveviewer-doesnt-show-top-bottom-of-listview-when-panenabled
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/71898754/pinch-to-zoom-listview-in-flutter

### Proposal

To me there seems to be three ways to solve this. The first, which is the most simple method, is to add some extra argument to each sliver enabling or disabling zooming. I don't know how this would work with multiple slivers though, so it doesn't seem ideal. The second to to add an argument to `CustomScrollView` that allows zooming. This seems like where the option _should_ be, from a user perspective, but I can't say it how feasible that is. The third is some new widget, for example, `ZoomView`, that allows all its children to be both zoomed and scrolled. I would much prefer the last solution because it can work with existing custom scrolling widgets that people may already be using for navigation, for example. Here's what that would look like:

```dart
ZoomView(
  maxZoomWidth: maxZoomWidth, //some options to possibly add to this widget
  maxZoomHeight: maxZoomHeight,
  opacityScrollBars: opacityScrollBars,
  doubleTapZoom: true,
  child: ListView.builder(
      physics:  const ScrollPhysics() //no need to do anything here
      itemCount: 10000000,
      itemBuilder: (context, index) {
        return Container(
          //enable to observe that the list rebuilds on every scroll
          //color: Colors.primaries[Random().nextInt(Colors.primaries.length)],
          child: Center(
              child: Text("text $index")
          ),
        );
      }
  )
)
```

The zoom view would know that two fingers always sets the zoom scale (rather than equal the vectors out as is the case with flutter scrolling in general, see https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/11884#issuecomment-1624431066). It would not distinguish between scrolling the viewport and panning the current view of the viewport – it would always scroll. To me, that seems to be the difference between `InteractiveViewer` and the proposed `ZoomView`. `InteractiveViewer` pans an image while `ZoomVIew` zooms an existing viewport. One last point that I want to make is that `InteractiveViewer.builder` is not a good option on its own because it doesn't help with existing `CustomScrollView` lists. We should be able to make an existing viewport zoomable with as little work as possible. This would allow this to work with existing packages like eg. https://pub.dev/packages/scrollable_positioned_list , https://pub.dev/packages/grouped_list ect. The decision for a given list to be zoomable is not so great that it should warrant a separate widget. 

edit: I wrote a package here https://pub.dev/packages/zoom_view

... to make ownership semantics more clear and not rely on raw pointers where we don't need to.

See below:

```h
const char* GLErrorToString(GLenum value);
bool GLErrorIsFatal(GLenum value);

struct AutoErrorCheck {
  const PFNGLGETERRORPROC error_fn;
  const char* name;

  AutoErrorCheck(PFNGLGETERRORPROC error, const char* name)
      : error_fn(error), name(name) {}

  ~AutoErrorCheck() {
    if (error_fn) {
      auto error = error_fn();
      if (error == GL_NO_ERROR) {
        return;
      }
      if (GLErrorIsFatal(error)) {
        FML_LOG(FATAL) << "Fatal GL Error " << GLErrorToString(error) << "("
                       << error << ")"
                       << " encountered on call to " << name;
      } else {
        FML_LOG(ERROR) << "GL Error " << GLErrorToString(error) << "(" << error
                       << ")"
                       << " encountered on call to " << name;
      }
    }
  }
};

template <class T>
struct GLProc {
  using GLFunctionType = T;

  //----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  /// The name of the GL function.
  ///
  const char* name = nullptr;
```

